        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Spatial resolution/Setup:
Based on the near-infrared image (Fig.1), the largest extension of that structure is 0.25''. To be able to locate the origin of the CO emission with respect to the structure found in the near-infrared, that is near the star, a resolution of 0.12'' (the finest resolution at this band) is needed. However, we expect that the CO envelope will be slightly more extended in the mm regime than the thermal emission seen in mid-infrared (&gt; 2'') but does fall within the maximum recoverable scale offered with the 12-m configuration.

Spectral resolution/Setup:
Observations are proposed on the 12CO(3-2) line at 345.795 GHz. With the chosen center frequencies, we can also cover 13CO(3-2) line at 330.587 GHz in the lower sideband. The 13CO isotope has not been detected before in L2 Pup, but at an expected 12CO/13CO-line ratio of 10 and the requested sensitivity, the detection of its brightest features is feasible. For bright and optically thick (in 12CO) structures, it is helpful to simultaneously probe the more optically thin regions (in 13CO). The expansion velocity of L2 Pup has been found to be 2.5-3 km/s. The requested spectral resolution at 0.4 km/s will allow precise high resolution measurements of the complicated dynamical processes within the circumstellar environment. Further on, two broad spectral windows have been selected for continuum emission (at 332.7 and 344.3 GHz). This will probe the dust emission and thus the location of the central star with respect to the molecular gas.

Sensitivity:
Single-dish observations with the JCMT, where the beam size was 13'', gave a flux density for CO(3-2) of 62 Jy (Kerschbaum &amp; Olofsson 1999). Based on the thermal dust emission from the source, we expect the extent of the CO emission to be no larger than 3'' resulting in a flux density of &gt;100 mJy at 0.12'' assuming a smooth brightness distribution across the whole extent of the emitting region. We aim for a sensitivity of 5 mJy to be able to detect also the weaker 13CO line. For the latter, we could also perform spectral binning during the analysis, if the emission is indeed weak (see comment above on spectral setup).</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
