    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>L2 Pup is an O-rich semi-regular variable that experienced a dimming event nearly 20 years ago that was thought to be due to dust formation. Recent interferometric observations of L2 Pup in the near infrared have revealed a toroidal structure with a size of less than 0.3'' at 2.30 micron. This has been the first detection of a toroidal structure in CO within 2 stellar radii from an O-rich AGB star. The gaseous structure is interwoven with dust. L2 Pup has one of the slowest outflows ever seen in an AGB star (&lt;3 km/s; CO(3-2)) but a spatio-kinematical study has never been performed before on this nearby star (64+/-4 pc). We now aim to probe in the mm-regime with ALMA, at both high spatial and spectral resolutions, the CO torus of L2 Pup beyond 2 stellar radii from the star, in order to (i) pinpoint the origin of the mm emitting gas, (ii) separate the slow wind from potential faster outflows, (iii) verify whether the torus is expanding or rotating. The last case is indicative of binarity and such a detection will be the first combined (near-IR + mm) study of a rotating torus in a binary AGB star.</prp:abstract>
